== Minor characters ==

I propose either deleting each or merging minor characters in one article which is redirected to by the individual pages.  [[User:John Reaves|John Reaves]] 06:35, 2 January 2007 (UTC)
:This discussion is now at [[Talk:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]. -[[User:Withinfocus|<font color="#000000">'''within'''</font>]][[User talk:Withinfocus|<font color="#7A7A7A">'''focus'''</font>]] 23:26, 2 January 2007 (UTC)

== Characters not added ==

An anonymous editor recently added a number of characters and items to the Staff section. Some I have retained, but others I have had to back out. The standard edit line is not long enough to include my rationale, so I have put that information here.

*Bathsheba Babbling (Ancient Runes): While we know that Bathsheba did write the Ancient Runes text, we don't know that she is actually teaching the course; the name never comes up in the context of her being the teacher.

*Alecto and Amycus Carrow - The fact that these two are Death Eaters is something of a spoiler.

*Neville Longbottom. The fact that he survives to become Herbology master is more than a bit of a spoiler.

I am not entirely happy about leaving Professor Kettleburn or Wilkie Twycross in, as Kettleburn is mentioned only once in passing, and Twycross is actually a Ministry employee. However, I don't have sufficient reason to remove Twycross from the list, as he does teach at Hogwarts, and Kettleburn is saved by his more extensive appearances in ''The Tales of Beedle the Bard''. [[User:Chazz|Chazz]] <small>([[User talk:Chazz|talk]])</small> 20:43, 9 May 2010 (UTC)

:Another editor has added Professor Tofty, Griselda Marchbanks, Tiberius Ogden, and Eddie Carmichael. While all of these characters are very minor, Marchbanks in particular has a large enough role to warrant keeping her, even if only just; and all of them are at least as much present as Wilkie Twycross, mentioned above, and so I can't justify removing them. [[User:Chazz|Chazz]] <small>([[User talk:Chazz|talk]])</small> 18:55, 16 March 2011 (UTC)

::Twice now anonymous editors have added Astoria Greengrass. I have reverted both times. Reasoning is this: The only mention of Astoria is in a family tree drawn up by Rowling after completion of the final book. We quite literally know nothing about her apart from the fact that she married [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Draco Malfoy|Draco Malfoy]] at some time after the close of the seventh book: was she a member of Slytherin House? Did she even attend Hogwarts? We don't know. Anything we were to write about her would perforce be speculation, and not something that would enhance our understanding of the Potter literature. [[User:Chazz|Chazz]] <small>([[User talk:Chazz|talk]])</small> 21:35, 18 December 2011 (UTC)

== "Next Generation" characters ==

I noticed that no one has contributed to this topic lately, and I was wondering if we should add any of the "next generation" characters mentioned in the Epilogue of Deathly Hallows - particularly Harry, Ron, and Hermione's children. [[User:Mollyingdc|Mollyingdc]] ([[User talk:Mollyingdc|discuss]] • [[Special:Contributions/Mollyingdc|contribs]]) 15:21, 22 July 2013 (UTC)
:While there hadn't been any plan to add them, because of the minor role they had, on reflection we do have characters with smaller roles even than them -- someone mentioned who was simply seen at the Sorting and never again, for instance. If you want to add them, please feel free; there is information and guidelines at [[Talk:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]], and there's a link on that page to the prepared frameworks. If you do choose to add them, I'd greatly appreciate it if you would put links to the new pages in one spot, e.g. under a "Next Generation" header of the Characters page, so that I (or someone) can properly include them in the print version and various watch lists. [[User:Chazz|Chazz]] <small>([[User talk:Chazz|talk]])</small> 16:02, 22 July 2013 (UTC)

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Occlumency| type=Method| features=Provides blocking of mind-reading| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Order of the Phoenix|''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix'']]|}}
== Overview ==
'''''Occlumency''''' is the ability to block one's mind from a Legilimens.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
Occlumency is the counter to [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Legilimency|Legilimency]], of which [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Lord Voldemort|Voldemort]] is a master. Characters like [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Severus Snape]] use Occlumency to hide their intentions. [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Harry Potter|Harry Potter]] is taught Occlumency lessons in ''Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix''. Both Snape and [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Albus Dumbledore|Dumbledore]] are accomplished Occlumens.
== Analysis ==
It is certain that Harry's ability to block his thoughts from Snape and Voldemort are not being helped by Snape's lessons. Harry's scar seems to prickle constantly after his lessons start, though that may be coincidence; it is at about the time that his Occlumency lessons start that Voldemort becomes aware that Harry can see into his mind on occasion, and it is shortly after that when Voldemort starts actively trying to get Harry into the Ministry. It is entirely possible that Harry's increased reaction may be due to increased probing from Voldemort. However, all through the lessons we see that Harry is unable to prevent Snape from viewing his memories, and at the end of [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Half-Blood Prince/Chapter 28|''Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince'']], we see that Snape is able to block any of Harry's spells before he can complete it, because of Snape's being able to read his intentions.
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
There is some question as to whether Occlumency would even work for Harry against Voldemort. Occlumency is designed to prevent an outside mind from being able to read what is happening within your mind, but as we learn in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Deathly Hallows/Chapter 33|''Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows'']], there is actually a fragment of Voldemort's soul within Harry. Does that bit of shared soul provide more access to Harry's mind than simple Legilimency? Harry never finds out, as he is never placed in a position again where he has to try and block Voldemort from his mind.
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Neapolitan}}
=='O tiémpo e 'o calannàrio (time and the calendar)== ==='O rilorrgio (the clock)=== {| class="wikitable" |style="width:100px", bgcolor="#e9e3c5"| '''English''' |style="width:100px", bgcolor="#e9e3c5"|'''Neapolitan''' |- |align="left"|a second |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'nu siconno |- |align="left"|a minute |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'nu minuto |- |align="left"|a half-hour |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'na mez óra |- |align="left"|an hour |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'n óra |}
==='A semmàna (the week)=== {| class="wikitable" |style="width:100px", bgcolor="#e9e3c5"| '''English''' |style="width:100px", bgcolor="#e9e3c5"|'''Neapolitan''' |- |align="left"|day |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'o juorno |- |align="left"|days |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'e juorne |- |align="left"|morning |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'a matina |- |align="left"|tomorrow morning |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|dimanummatina |- |align="left"|noon, midday |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'o miezojuòrno |- |align="left"|afternoon |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'a cuntróra |- |align="left"|evening |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'a séra |- |align="left"|last evening |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|ajeressera |- |align="left"|tomorrow evening |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|dimanassera |- |align="left"|night |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|'a notte |- |align="left"|yesterday |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|ajere |- |align="left"|the day before yesterday |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|ll'autriere |- |align="left"|today |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|ogge |- |align="left"|tomorrow |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|dimane/craje† |- |align="left"|the day after tomorrow |align="left", bgcolor="#c9c8e9"|doppedimane/pescraje† |}
†''Dimane'' is used more in Naples proper whereas ''craje'' is more common in northern Calabria. ''Craje'' comes from the Latin adverb ''cras'' (tomorrow) while ''dimane'' is constructed from the Latin words ''de'' + ''mane'' (mane= morning, ''de mane''- in the morning) in the same manner as it is many other Romance languages.
